Welcome back to a Super Sunday edition of Dry Powder. I=E2=80=99m Bill
Cohan, and I don=E2=80=99t have any =E2=80=9Ccarried interest=E2=80=9D of m=
y own in tonight=E2=80=99s game since the Patriots are in a half-decade dry=
 spell. Nevertheless, I=E2=80=99ll be watching our former star quarterback =
and current Las Vegas Raiders minority owner, Tom Brady, in the Fox booth t=
onight and exchanging texts with some owners, current and perhaps future.

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, let=E2=80=99s pour one out for
David Rubenstein, the newish owner of the Baltimore Orioles and my fellow D=
ukie. (Indeed, Cameron Indoor is now a veritable anteroom for his beautiful=
 gift, the Rubenstein Pavilion, among his other endowments to the universit=
y.) David, a co-founder of the Carlyle Group, whose philanthropic largesse =
extends far beyond his beloved alma mater, is suddenly, it turns out, the o=
utgoing chair of the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. You may have m=
issed the announcement
Friday night, but Donald Trump has decided that the Kennedy Center needs to=
 be Made Great Again, too, and so abruptly replaced Rubenstein as the cente=
r=E2=80=99s chairman, with=E2=80=94you guessed it=E2=80=94himself. (I suppo=
se it could have been worse. He could have picked Kid Rock, and he still mi=
ght.) As far as I can tell, David has handled his defenestration with muted=
 grace. But I=E2=80=99m curious to watch this continue to play out. =C2=A0

=C2=A0

The new president=E2=80=99s antics provide the leitmotif for tonight=E2=80=
=99s email. As loyal readers will recall, the .001-percent crowd on Wall St=
reet has been generally happy with Trump II, save for the whole January 6 m=
ass-pardon affair and the post-DCA jet-helicopter collision presser filled =
with stream-of-consciousness nonsense about D.E.I. But on Thursday, a third=
 beef entered the picture: Trump=E2=80=99s unexpected
attack on the coveted carried interest loophole, the part of the U.S. tax c=
ode that has, over the past few decades, turned the private equity industry=
 into a billionaire factory. I surveyed my most esteemed private equity sou=
rces and friends, however, and you=E2=80=99ll be very surprised about what =
they confessed.

=C2=A0

But first=E2=80=A6

* Trump
enters the E.T.F. game: Trump Media and Technology Group, the company that =
runs Truth Social, is getting into finance, it seems, taking a page from El=
on Musk, who has promised to turn X into a payments platform. (Trump and hi=
s unofficial co-president seem to be having a mind meld these days.) Is thi=
s market pivot an indication that subscale social media companies have dim =
prospects as purely ad-funded concerns? That=E2=80=99s sure what it seems l=
ike. X, for instance, has also moved
into subscriptions and integrated A.I., through Musk=E2=80=99s xAI and its =
Grok chatbot=E2=80=94a move that seems to have boosted the company=E2=80=99=
s on-paper valuation via xAI=E2=80=99s $50 billion valuation.=C2=A0

For its part, Trump Media announced on Thursday that the company had applie=
d to register trademarks for brand names connected to the launch of customi=
zed exchange-traded funds, among other financial products. The hoped-for of=
ferings of =E2=80=9CTruth.Fi=E2=80=9D apparently include a Made in America =
E.T.F., a U.S. Energy
Independence E.T.F., and a Bitcoin Plus E.T.F.=E2=80=94all in keeping with =
MAGA themes and priorities. The company seems to be pledging $250 million t=
oward its new fintech effort. Financial wizard Devin Nunes, the former rabb=
le-rousing congressman and C.E.O. of Trump Media and Technology Group, said=
 in a statement, =E2=80=9CWe aim to give investors a means to invest in Ame=
rican energy, manufacturing, and other firms that provide a competitive alt=
ernative to the woke funds and debanking
problems that you find throughout the market. We=E2=80=99re exploring a ran=
ge of ways to differentiate our products, including strategies related to b=
itcoin. We will continue to fine-tune our intended product suite to develop=
 the optimal mix of offerings for investors who believe in America First pr=
inciples.=E2=80=9D How lovely.=C2=A0

On Thursday, when the news surfaced, the Trump Media stock was up nearly 7.=
5 percent. But on Friday, it recessed nearly 4 percent. Still, by some mira=
cle, Trump Media has a
market value of $6.75 billion=E2=80=94down nearly 10 percent since the inau=
guration, but up nearly 22 percent in the past six months. The company lost=
 more than $100 million last year. What a great country=E2=80=A6

And now, the main event=E2=80=A6

Trump=E2=80=99s Carried Interest Insurrection ( https://puck.news/trumps-ca=
rried-interest-insurrection/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2=
F9%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
**********************************************************
Trump=E2=80=99s Carried Interest Insurrection ( https://puck.news/trumps-ca=
rried-interest-insurrection/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2=
F9%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
**********************************************************

Wall Street hasn=E2=80=99t had much beef with Trump 2.0 thus far, outside o=
f the J6 pardons and
his misguided response to the midair collision over DCA. But now that he=E2=
=80=99s taking on the carried interest loophole, things may change.

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F9%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F9%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Last week, I shared a
conversation ( https://puck.news/wall-street-is-still-aboard-the-trump-trai=
n/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F9%2F25%29&utm_content=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) with one of my most faithf=
ul Wall Street correspondents, who relayed the surprisingly bipartisan supp=
ort that Donald Trump appeared to be enjoying among the top machers of the =
financial services industry. Other sources confirmed that the banker and in=
vestor class is pretty much happy with the first three weeks of Trump II, s=
ave for a few
offenses, including the blanket pardoning of January 6 insurrectionists and=
 Trump=E2=80=99s bizarre decision to blame the deadly plane-helicopter coll=
ision above the Potomac on D.E.I. policies. The dismantling of USAID and ot=
her parts of the federal bureaucracy, the alleged tampering with U.S. Treas=
ury payment systems=E2=80=94these issues elicited little more than a shrug.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Now, however, it appears the president has
crossed the line by targeting the most sacred cow in the roughly $6 trillio=
n private equity industry: the carried interest loophole. On Thursday, Trum=
p proposed eliminating the provision in the tax code that allows the =E2=80=
=9Calternative assets=E2=80=9D crowd to enjoy a luxurious 23.8 percent capi=
tal gains tax treatment on by far the biggest part of their compensation, r=
ather than the ordinary top income tax rate of 40.8 percent or so.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Private equity investors have benefitted from this preferential treatment s=
ince the leveraged-buyout bonanza started 40 years ago. As most of my reade=
rs know, =E2=80=9Ccarried interest=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94or =E2=80=9Ccarry,=E2=
=80=9D tout court=E2=80=94accrues to the general partners of a private equi=
ty fund and is, generally speaking, 20 percent of a fund=E2=80=99s profits =
after a minimum return is met. (The other 80 percent of the profits go to t=
he limited partners, who actually put up most of the capital
for the fund.) The simple brilliance of the P.E. deal structure=E2=80=94one=
 in which investors make lavish returns on borrowed money and then enjoy hi=
ghly discounted tax treatment on their windfalls=E2=80=94explains how the i=
ndustry became one of the greatest wealth-creation vehicles in modern histo=
ry. One Oxford University professor has described the private equity indust=
ry as a =E2=80=9Cbillionaire=E2=80=99s factory.=E2=80=9D Indeed, Steve Schw=
arzman, the co-founder of the powerful Blackstone Group, is worth around
$55 billion these days. The duo who founded KKR are worth around $20 billio=
n each. The three co-founders of Apollo Global Management are each worth mo=
re than $10 billion.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Usually, it=E2=80=99s the Democrats who bang the drum for the repeal of the=
 carried interest benefit. And every time, the powerful private equity lobb=
y in Washington, generally led by the American Investment Council, manages =
to save it.
Trump, however, proposed closing the loophole once before, in 2017, but the=
 lobbyists won that fight as well. (There was a compromise of sorts, with a=
sset managers agreeing to hold their investments for a longer period of tim=
e in order to get the more favorable tax treatment.)

=C2=A0

But despite the events of Trump I, the idea seemed to come out of the blue =
on Thursday. Trump didn=E2=80=99t mention =E2=80=9Ccarried interest=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cprivate equity=E2=80=9D
during the 2024 campaign, and the denizens of K Street seemed surprised tha=
t he raised it again last week. This time, however, Trump might have their =
number, since the Republicans in Congress seem disinclined to stand up to h=
im on anything, and Democrats have long favored abolishing the provision. D=
emocratic senator Tammy Baldwin of Wisconsin introduced legislation on Thur=
sday to eliminate the benefit. That same day, Democratic House members Mari=
e Gluesenkamp
Perez of Washington state and Don Beyer of Virginia introduced similar legi=
slation. Could the day of reckoning be nigh?

The
$14 Billion Question
--------------------

As you might imagine, this latest attack on carried interest hasn=E2=80=99t=
 gone down well with
everyone. One retired private equity executive, who I found down in Palm Be=
ach, seemed to be at a loss for why Trump would suggest biting the hand tha=
t feeds him. Another private equity founder also had no explanation why the=
 president would propose this kind of reform. =E2=80=9CAll I know is, I=E2=
=80=99m getting the worst of both worlds if this happens,=E2=80=9D he said,=
 given that he didn=E2=80=99t support Trump. =E2=80=9CSchwarzman and all hi=
s other P.E. backers have to be a little pissed.=E2=80=9D However, a longti=
me Wall Street
lawyer who often works with =E2=80=9Calternative asset=E2=80=9D firms surpr=
ised me by saying that Trump is =E2=80=9Cright on carried interest.=E2=80=
=9D But won=E2=80=99t the =E2=80=9Cdonor class=E2=80=9D be angry? I wondere=
d. Yes they would, he agreed, =E2=80=9Cbut fuck them.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

For the moment, as you might imagine, the big guys are lying low. A spokesp=
erson for Blackstone said the firm would have no comment on Trump=E2=80=99s=
 proposal. A spokesman for Apollo co-founder
Josh Harris, who faces a double whammy as both a private equity investor an=
d the owner of several sports teams, including the Philadelphia 76ers and t=
he Washington Commanders, also did not respond to a request for comment. (A=
lso on Thursday, White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt said Trump wa=
nts to eliminate the amortization tax break for owners of pro sports teams.=
)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

A spokesman for Marc Rowan, the C.E.O. of Apollo, did not respond to a requ=
est for comment. But Marc did tell me, during an interview in September 202=
3, =E2=80=9CWhy do you think the carried interest tax comes up every time t=
here=E2=80=99s an election? Because the Dems know it=E2=80=99s good for the=
 unions and the Republicans know it=E2=80=99s good for squeezing money out =
of private equity. And the last thing they want to do is actually solve the=
 issue because, God forbid, they wouldn't be
able to fundraise off of it. Why solve anything? Why not just have emotiona=
l issues that you can perpetuate?=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Indeed, my survey of elite private equity executives dredged up similar sen=
timents=E2=80=94no one wanted the loophole closed, obviously, but they felt=
 that Trump was being Trump, appealing to his base, and they are perfectly =
happy to be pilloried as long as the president doesn=E2=80=99t actually fol=
low
through and pick their pockets. Of course, closing the carried interest loo=
phole isn=E2=80=99t quite going to satisfy the budget-balancing appetites o=
f Elon Musk and his DOGE droogs. According to the Congressional Budget Offi=
ce, eliminating the carried interest provision would only raise about $14 b=
illion in new tax revenue over the next decade=E2=80=94a pittance, perhaps,=
 given the nearly $2 trillion federal budget deficit. =E2=80=9CAfter the pr=
esident=E2=80=99s historic tax
reform, the private equity industry invested over $5.6 trillion in the Amer=
ican economy=E2=80=94supporting over 36,000 small businesses,=E2=80=9D Drew=
 Maloney, the C.E.O. of the American Investment Council, said in a diplomat=
ically worded statement. =E2=80=9CWe encourage the Trump Administration and=
 Congress to keep this sound tax police in place.=E2=80=9D In other words, =
please don=E2=80=99t rock the boat, Donald.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Another
private equity founder, who also did not support Trump, told me that the pr=
oposal to repeal the provision was =E2=80=9Csmart politics,=E2=80=9D and wh=
ile he was surprised by Trump=E2=80=99s move, he wasn=E2=80=99t all that su=
rprised. Trump =E2=80=9Creally doesn=E2=80=99t like Wall Street types=E2=80=
=9D because =E2=80=9Cthey didn=E2=80=99t support him=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94altho=
ugh many did, in fact, due to their abject hatred of the Biden-Harris admin=
istration=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cand they are classic elitists,=E2=80=9D he said,=
 adding: =E2=80=9CBut let=E2=80=99s see if Schwarzman goes
to work on him.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I wouldn=E2=80=99t yet bet against the Schwarzmans of the world being able =
to reorient Trump on this issue, especially because Trump loves tweaking th=
ese guys when he can, only to watch them bend a knee when he gives them wha=
t they want. Meanwhile, there=E2=80=99s plenty of schadenfreude elsewhere o=
n Wall Street. Another of my faithful correspondents, who is not in the alt=
ernative asset
space, seemed positively giddy about the suggestion that the loophole could=
 be closed. =E2=80=9CThere is a god!=E2=80=9D she wrote. =E2=80=9CAll those=
 assholes who voted for Trump will have to pay more in taxes without the ca=
rried interest deduction. I can=E2=80=99t wait to see Ackman=E2=80=99s whin=
y tweets.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

For the record, so far, Bill Ackman has been silent on the topic. On Friday=
, he tweeted to his (now) 1.6 million followers that
he=E2=80=99d acquired 30.3 million shares of Uber as his hedge fund=E2=80=
=99s latest big bet. =E2=80=9CI have been a long-term customer and admirer =
of Uber beginning when Edward Norton showed me the app in its early days,=
=E2=80=9D he wrote. Uber=E2=80=99s stock was up almost 7 percent on the new=
s, giving Bill a one-day profit of roughly $140 million. So far, all good.

