9999999997px;"><strong>The
$14 Billion Question</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">As you might imagine, this latest attack on carried interest hasn=E2=80=
=99t gone down well with
<em>everyone</em>. One retired private equity executive, who I found down i=
n Palm Beach, seemed to be at a loss for why Trump would suggest biting the=
 hand that feeds him. Another private equity founder also had no explanatio=
n why the president would propose this kind of reform. =E2=80=9CAll I know =
is, I=E2=80=99m getting the worst of both worlds if this happens,=E2=80=9D =
he said, given that he didn=E2=80=99t support Trump. =E2=80=9CSchwarzman an=
d all his other P.E. backers have to be a little pissed.=E2=80=9D However, =
a longtime Wall Street
lawyer who often works with =E2=80=9Calternative asset=E2=80=9D firms surpr=
ised me by saying that Trump is =E2=80=9Cright on carried interest.=E2=80=
=9D But won=E2=80=99t the =E2=80=9Cdonor class=E2=80=9D be angry? I wondere=
d. Yes they would, he agreed, =E2=80=9Cbut fuck them.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">For the moment, as you might imagine, the big guys are lying low. =
A spokesperson for Blackstone said the firm would have no comment on Trump=
=E2=80=99s proposal. A spokesman for Apollo co-founder
<strong>Josh Harris</strong>, who faces a double whammy as both a private e=
quity investor <em>and</em> the owner of several sports teams, including th=
e Philadelphia 76ers and the Washington Commanders, also did not respond to=
 a request for comment. (Also on Thursday, White House Press Secretary <str=
ong>Karoline Leavitt </strong>said Trump wants to eliminate the amortizatio=
n tax break for owners of pro sports teams.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">A spokesman for <strong>Marc Rowan</strong>, the C.E.O.=
 of Apollo, did not respond to a request for comment. But Marc did tell me,=
 during an interview in September 2023, =E2=80=9CWhy do you think the carri=
ed interest tax comes up every time there=E2=80=99s an election? Because th=
e Dems know it=E2=80=99s good for the unions and the Republicans know it=E2=
=80=99s good for squeezing money out of private equity. And the last thing =
they want to do is actually solve the issue because, God forbid, they would=
n&#39;t be
able to fundraise off of it. Why solve anything? Why not just have emotiona=
l issues that you can perpetuate?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Indeed, my s=
urvey of elite private equity executives dredged up similar sentiments=E2=
=80=94no one wanted the loophole closed, <em>obviously</em>, but they felt =
that Trump was being Trump, appealing to his base, and they are perfectly h=
appy to be pilloried as long as the president doesn=E2=80=99t actually foll=
ow
through and pick their pockets. Of course, closing the carried interest loo=
phole isn=E2=80=99t <em>quite </em>going to satisfy the budget-balancing ap=
petites of <strong>Elon</strong> <strong>Musk </strong>and his DOGE droogs.=
 According to the Congressional Budget Office, eliminating the carried inte=
rest provision would only raise about $14 billion in new tax revenue over t=
he next <em>decade</em>=E2=80=94a pittance, perhaps, given the nearly $2 tr=
illion federal budget deficit. =E2=80=9CAfter the president=E2=80=99s histo=
ric tax
reform, the private equity industry invested over $5.6 trillion in the Amer=
ican economy=E2=80=94supporting over 36,000 small businesses,=E2=80=9D <str=
ong>Drew Maloney</strong>, the C.E.O. of the American Investment Council, s=
aid in a diplomatically worded statement. =E2=80=9CWe encourage the Trump A=
dministration and Congress to keep this sound tax police in place.=E2=80=9D=
 In other words, please don=E2=80=99t rock the boat, Donald.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">Another
private equity founder, who also did not support Trump, told me that the pr=
oposal to repeal the provision was =E2=80=9Csmart politics,=E2=80=9D and wh=
ile he was surprised by Trump=E2=80=99s move, he wasn=E2=80=99t all <em>tha=
t</em> surprised. Trump =E2=80=9Creally doesn=E2=80=99t like Wall Street ty=
pes=E2=80=9D because =E2=80=9Cthey didn=E2=80=99t support him=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94although many did, in fact, due to their abject hatred of the <strong=
>Biden</strong>-<strong>Harris</strong> administration=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cand=
 they are classic elitists,=E2=80=9D he said, adding: =E2=80=9CBut let=E2=
=80=99s see if Schwarzman goes
to work on him.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I wouldn=E2=80=99t yet b=
et against the Schwarzmans of the world being able to reorient Trump on thi=
s issue, especially because Trump loves tweaking these guys when he can, on=
ly to watch them bend a knee when he gives them what they want. Meanwhile, =
there=E2=80=99s plenty of <em>schadenfreude </em>elsewhere on Wall Street. =
Another of my faithful correspondents, who is not in the alternative asset
space, seemed positively giddy about the suggestion that the loophole could=
 be closed. =E2=80=9CThere is a god!=E2=80=9D she wrote. =E2=80=9CAll those=
 assholes who voted for Trump will have to pay more in taxes without the ca=
rried interest deduction. I can=E2=80=99t wait to see <strong>Ackman</stron=
g>=E2=80=99s whiny tweets.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">For the record, so far, Bill Ac=
kman has been silent on the topic. On Friday, he tweeted to his (now) 1.6 m=
illion followers that
he=E2=80=99d acquired 30.3 million shares of Uber as his hedge fund=E2=80=
=99s latest big bet. =E2=80=9CI have been a long-term customer and admirer =
of Uber beginning when <strong>Edward Norton</strong> showed me the app in =
its early days,=E2=80=9D he wrote. Uber=E2=80=99s stock was up almost 7 per=
cent on the news, giving Bill a one-day profit of roughly $140 million. So =
far, all good.</p></div>
